main event: On July 11, 1957, in Wellsboro, Pennsylvania, a round, basketball-sized, white object was observed fading in the west over a period of 1 hour and 15 minutes. The object remained at the same altitude for around 5 minutes, indicating a fixed position before fading away.
interesting points: The observation was made by a civilian and was conducted through ground visual means with the aid of binoculars.
The weather at the time of the sighting was clear, with surface winds ranging from 13 knots to 75 knots at different altitudes.

The conclusion of the report stated that there was insufficient data for evaluation, and it did not definitively identify the object as a balloon, aircraft, astronomical object, or other known entity.
The report was disseminated to various military and intelligence commands for assessment, including the Air Defense Command, Air Technical Intelligence Center, and Intel HQ USAF.
There is a mention of a witness, Frank, but the identifying information is not fully discernible due to the document's condition.
